{"id":"1707.08830","submitter":"G J Sreejith","authors":"G J Sreejith, Yuhe Zhang and J K Jain","title":"Surprising robustness of particle-hole symmetry for composite fermion\n  liquids","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. B 96, 125149 (2017)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevB.96.125149","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.str-el","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We report on fixed phase diffusion Monte Carlo calculations that show that,\neven for a large amount of Landau level mixing, the energies of the Pfaffian\nand anti-Pfaffian phases remain very nearly the same, as also do the excitation\ngaps at $1/3$ and $2/3$. These results, combined with previous theoretical and\nexperimental investigations, indicate that particle hole (PH) symmetry for\ncomposite fermion states is much more robust than a priori expected, emerging\neven in models that explicitly break PH symmetry. We provide insight into this\nfact by showing that the low energy physics of a generic repulsive 3-body\ninteraction is captured, to a large extent and over a range of filling factors,\nby a mean field approximation that maps it into a PH symmetric 2-body\ninteraction. This explains why Landau level mixing, which effectively generates\nsuch a generic 3-body interaction, is inefficient in breaking PH symmetry. As a\nbyproduct, our results provide a systematic construction of a 2-body\ninteraction which produces, to a good approximation, the Pfaffian wave function\nas its ground state.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 27 Jul 2017 12:22:16 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-10-04"}
