{"id":"1707.08846","submitter":"Radostin Simitev","authors":"Radostin D. Simitev, Friedrich H. Busse","title":"Baroclinically-driven flows and dynamo action in rotating spherical\n  fluid shells","comments":"Original article; Accepted for publication in Geophysical and\n  Astrophysical Fluid Dynamics on 2017-07-26","journal-ref":"Geophys. Astrophys. Fluid Dyn., 111(5), pp 369-379 (2017)","doi":"10.1080/03091929.2017.1361945","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.flu-dyn astro-ph.SR","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The dynamics of stably stratified stellar radiative zones is of considerable\ninterest due to the availability of increasingly detailed observations of Solar\nand stellar interiors. This article reports the first non-axisymmetric and\ntime-dependent simulations of flows of anelastic fluids driven by baroclinic\ntorques in stably stratified rotating spherical shells -- a system serving as\nan elemental model of a stellar radiative zone. With increasing baroclinicity a\nsequence of bifurcations from simpler to more complex flows is found in which\nsome of the available symmetries of the problem are broken subsequently. The\npoloidal component of the flow grows relative to the dominant toroidal\ncomponent with increasing baroclinicity. The possibility of magnetic field\ngeneration thus arises and this paper proceeds to provide some indications for\nself-sustained dynamo action in baroclinically-driven flows. We speculate that\nmagnetic fields in stably stratified stellar interiors are thus not necessarily\nof fossil origin as it is often assumed.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 27 Jul 2017 12:55:10 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-05-13"}
